"1194","1170":"1170","vers 1153":"circa 1153","1125":"1125","1079":"1079","1134":"1134","Jerusalem, Kingdom of Jerusalem":"Jerusalem, Westelijke Jordaanoever, Palestina","Alluyes, Eure-et-Loir, Centre-Val de Loire, Francia":"Alluyes, Eure-et-Loir, Centre, Frankrijk","Montmirail, Marne, Grand Est, France":"Montmirail, Marne, Grand Est, Frankrijk","Palestine":"Palestina"},"en":{"1125–about 1170":"1125–about 1170","1125–1170":"1125–1170","1134–1164":"1134–1164","1140–Female":"1140–Deceased","1130–1185":"1130–1185","1153–1194":"1153–1194","1079–1140":"1079–1140","–Female":"Deceased","about 1170":"about 1170","après 1140":"after 1140","1153":"1153","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1194":"1194","1170":"1170","vers 1153":"about 1153","1125":"1125","1079":"1079","1134":"1134","Jerusalem, Kingdom of Jerusalem":"Jerusalem, West Bank, Palestine","Alluyes, Eure-et-Loir, Centre-Val de Loire, Francia":"Alluyes, Eure-et-Loir, Centre, France","Montmirail, Marne, Grand Est, France":"Montmirail, Marne, Grand Est, France","Palestine":"Palestine","nameMeanings":[{"name":"GOUET","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Slawomir, Beata, Jolanta, Karol.  German Rainer.","French and Polish (of French origin): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Hugo(n)</i>, French form of   Hugh  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hugh","meanings":["English, Welsh, and Scottish (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Hue</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Hugo</i> (ultimately derived from <i>hugi-</i> ‘mind, spirit’). This was a very popular name in England after the Norman Conquest, partly due to the reputation of Saint Hugh of Lincoln (1140–1200), who was born in Burgundy and who established the first Carthusian monastery in England.","Scottish and Irish: adopted as an Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Aodh</i>, a derivative of a Gaelic word meaning ‘fire’. See   Hughes  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surnames 邱 and 丘, based on their Hakka pronunciation; see   Qiu   1 and 2."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"IV","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Guillaume William IV GOUET de Montmirail was born in 1125, in Alluyes, Eure-et-Loir, Centre, France as the son of Guillaume William III Gouët Lord of Montmirail and Mabel Fitzroy. He had at least 1 daughter with Isabel Élisabeth of Blois and Champagne. He died about 1170, in Jerusalem, West Bank, Palestine, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1125–about 1170":"1125–umbes 1170","1125–1170":"1125–1170","1134–1164":"1134–1164","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","1130–1185":"1130–1185","1153–1194":"1153–1194","1079–1140":"1079–1140","–Female":"Surnud","about 1170":"umbes 1170","après 1140":"pärast 1140","1153":"1153","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1194":"1194","1170":"1170","vers 1153":"umbes 1153","1125":"1125","1079":"1079","1134":"1134","Jerusalem, Kingdom of Jerusalem":"J